# C++ Programming Projects

This folder contains C++ projects focused on modern software design, embedded applications, digital signal processing, wireless algorithms, real-time data processing, memory management, multithreading, communication protocols, testing, and performance analysis.

The current projects use structured software architecture, reusable classes, templates, Standard Library components, smart pointers, RAII, explicit error handling, automated builds, and organized testing.

The planned projects will extend the folder with fixed-point DSP, lock-free communication, deterministic memory management, wireless physical-layer processing, protocol frameworks, task scheduling, hardware abstraction, fault handling, and high-performance data pipelines.

## Objectives

The main objectives of this folder are to:

* design modular and maintainable C++ applications;
* create reusable classes and interfaces;
* apply object-oriented and generic programming;
* manage resources safely using RAII;
* use smart pointers and clear ownership rules;
* implement embedded, DSP, wireless, and communication applications;
* develop thread-safe and real-time-oriented software;
* create portable builds using CMake;
* verify software with unit, integration, stress, and performance tests;
* measure execution time, memory usage, latency, and throughput;
* demonstrate practical C++ skills for technical software positions.

## Technical Areas

The projects cover:

* C++17 and C++20;
* object-oriented programming;
* class design and encapsulation;
* composition and polymorphism;
* dependency injection;
* templates and generic programming;
* Standard Library containers and algorithms;
* smart pointers;
* RAII;
* move semantics;
* copy and move constructors;
* function objects and lambda expressions;
* callback interfaces;
* state machines;
* event-driven software;
* embedded C++;
* sensor-data processing;
* digital signal processing;
* fixed-point arithmetic;
* wireless and baseband algorithms;
* multithreading;
* mutexes and condition variables;
* atomic operations;
* lock-free data structures;
* custom memory allocators;
* communication protocols;
* hardware abstraction;
* software testing;
* static and dynamic analysis;
* performance profiling;
* CMake;
* GitHub Actions.

