# Software Architecture

Larger projects should use a layered structure.

```text
Application Layer
       |
       v
Service Layer
       |
       v
Algorithm or Protocol Layer
       |
       v
Platform Abstraction
       |
       v
Operating System or Hardware
```

A typical project may use:

```text
project-name/
│
├── include/
│   └── project/
│       ├── project.hpp
│       └── project_types.hpp
│
├── src/
│   ├── project.cpp
│   └── internal_module.cpp
│
├── tests/
│   ├── test_project.cpp
│   └── test_internal_module.cpp
│
├── examples/
│   └── example_application.cpp
│
├── benchmarks/
│   └── benchmark_project.cpp
│
├── docs/
│   └── architecture.md
│
├── CMakeLists.txt
└── README.md
```

## Interface Design

Public interfaces should expose only the operations required by calling modules.

Internal implementation details should remain private.

```cpp
class SignalProcessor
{
public:
    virtual ~SignalProcessor() = default;

    virtual void configure(
        const ProcessorConfiguration& configuration
    ) = 0;

    virtual ProcessingResult process(
        std::span<const float> input
    ) = 0;

    virtual void reset() = 0;
};
```

Different algorithm implementations can use the same public interface.

## Resource Management

Resources should be controlled using RAII.

Resources may include:

* dynamically allocated memory;
* files;
* threads;
* mutexes;
* sockets;
* device handles;
* communication channels.

Example:

```cpp
class FileHandle
{
public:
    explicit FileHandle(
        const std::filesystem::path& path
    );

    ~FileHandle();

    FileHandle(const FileHandle&) = delete;

    FileHandle& operator=(
        const FileHandle&
    ) = delete;

    FileHandle(FileHandle&& other) noexcept;

    FileHandle& operator=(
        FileHandle&& other
    ) noexcept;

private:
    std::FILE* handle_{nullptr};
};
```

The destructor releases the resource automatically.

## Smart Pointers

Use `std::unique_ptr` for exclusive ownership.

```cpp
auto processor =
    std::make_unique<FirFilter>(
        coefficients
    );
```

Use `std::shared_ptr` only when shared ownership is required.

```cpp
auto configuration =
    std::make_shared<SystemConfiguration>();
```

Use `std::weak_ptr` for non-owning references to shared objects.

Raw pointers may be used for non-owning access when ownership is clearly documented.

## Copy and Move Semantics

Classes that manage resources should define or disable copying and moving intentionally.

```cpp
class ProcessingBuffer
{
public:
    explicit ProcessingBuffer(
        std::size_t size
    );

    ProcessingBuffer(
        const ProcessingBuffer&
    ) = delete;

    ProcessingBuffer& operator=(
        const ProcessingBuffer&
    ) = delete;

    ProcessingBuffer(
        ProcessingBuffer&&
    ) noexcept = default;

    ProcessingBuffer& operator=(
        ProcessingBuffer&&
    ) noexcept = default;

private:
    std::unique_ptr<float[]> data_;
    std::size_t size_{0};
};
```

## Error Handling

Projects may use:

* exceptions;
* status enumerations;
* `std::optional`;
* `std::variant`;
* expected-style result objects.

### Example Status Type

```cpp
enum class Status
{
    Ok,
    InvalidArgument,
    NotInitialized,
    BufferFull,
    BufferEmpty,
    Timeout,
    DataCorruption,
    ResourceUnavailable,
    InternalError
};
```

### Example Result Structure

```cpp
template<typename T>
struct OperationResult
{
    Status status{Status::InternalError};

    std::optional<T> value;

    [[nodiscard]]
    bool success() const noexcept
    {
        return status == Status::Ok;
    }
};
```

# Coding Guidelines

The projects follow these practices:

* use clear class, function, and variable names;
* keep classes focused on one responsibility;
* prefer composition over unnecessary inheritance;
* apply `const` correctly;
* use `constexpr` for compile-time values;
* use `enum class` for strongly typed enumerations;
* use smart pointers for ownership;
* avoid unnecessary raw memory allocation;
* use RAII for resource handling;
* validate public-interface arguments;
* avoid uncontrolled global state;
* use move semantics for large objects;
* use Standard Library algorithms where appropriate;
* isolate platform-specific code;
* document assumptions and limitations;
* compile without warnings.

## Fixed-Width Integer Types

Embedded, DSP, and protocol projects should use `<cstdint>`.

```cpp
#include <cstdint>

std::uint8_t messageType{0};

std::int16_t sensorSample{0};

std::uint32_t timestampTicks{0};

std::int64_t accumulatedEnergy{0};
```

## Span-Based Interfaces

`std::span` can represent an external buffer without copying its data.

```cpp
Status processSamples(
    std::span<const std::int16_t> input,
    std::span<float> output
);
```

This keeps the buffer pointer and length together.

## Const Correctness

Functions that do not modify object state should be marked `const`.

```cpp
class Statistics
{
public:
    [[nodiscard]]
    double mean() const noexcept;

    [[nodiscard]]
    double variance() const noexcept;

    [[nodiscard]]
    std::size_t sampleCount() const noexcept;
};
```

## Compile-Time Constants

Use `constexpr` for values known during compilation.

```cpp
constexpr std::size_t fftSize = 1024;

constexpr double samplingFrequency = 30.72e6;

constexpr std::size_t maximumFrameSize = 4096;
```

# Build Instructions

The projects use CMake as the primary build system.

## Requirements

* GCC, Clang, or Microsoft Visual C++;
* C++17 or C++20 support;
* CMake;
* Git;
* optional unit-test framework;
* optional static-analysis tools.

## Configure

```bash
cmake -S . -B build
```

## Build

```bash
cmake --build build
```

## Release Build

```bash
cmake -S . -B build \
    -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release

cmake --build build
```

## Run Tests

```bash
ctest \
    --test-dir build \
    --output-on-failure
```

## GCC Example

```bash
g++ \
    -std=c++20 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -Wconversion \
    -Wshadow \
    -Wformat=2 \
    -Wundef \
    src/main.cpp \
    src/module.cpp \
    -Iinclude \
    -pthread \
    -o application
```

## Debug Build

```bash
g++ \
    -std=c++20 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -g3 \
    -O0 \
    src/main.cpp \
    src/module.cpp \
    -Iinclude \
    -pthread \
    -o application
```

## Optimized Build

```bash
g++ \
    -std=c++20 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -O2 \
    -DNDEBUG \
    src/main.cpp \
    src/module.cpp \
    -Iinclude \
    -pthread \
    -o application
```

## AddressSanitizer Build

```bash
g++ \
    -std=c++20 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -fsanitize=address,undefined \
    -fno-omit-frame-pointer \
    -g \
    src/main.cpp \
    src/module.cpp \
    -Iinclude \
    -pthread \
    -o application_sanitized
```

Run:

```bash
./application_sanitized
```

## ThreadSanitizer Build

```bash
g++ \
    -std=c++20 \
    -Wall \
    -Wextra \
    -Wpedantic \
    -fsanitize=thread \
    -g \
    src/main.cpp \
    src/module.cpp \
    -Iinclude \
    -pthread \
    -o application_thread_sanitized
```

# Testing Strategy

Each project should include structured verification rather than only one demonstration run.

Testing may include:

* unit testing;
* integration testing;
* interface testing;
* boundary-value testing;
* invalid-input testing;
* exception-path testing;
* resource-lifetime testing;
* concurrency stress testing;
* regression testing;
* performance benchmarking;
* fuzz testing.

## Unit Tests

Unit tests may validate:

* filter outputs;
* queue operations;
* state-machine transitions;
* CRC calculations;
* parser behaviour;
* allocator operation;
* error-condition handling;
* ownership transfer;
* move construction;
* object cleanup.

## Boundary Tests

Boundary tests may include:

* empty containers;
* one-element containers;
* maximum-capacity buffers;
* full queues;
* empty queues;
* zero-length input;
* maximum-size protocol frames;
* timer rollover;
* minimum and maximum numeric values.

## Invalid-Input Tests

Examples include:

* invalid configuration;
* malformed frames;
* unsupported message types;
* incorrect buffer sizes;
* invalid state transitions;
* corrupted CRC values;
* unavailable resources;
* invalid timing values.

## Resource-Lifetime Tests

Resource tests should verify:

* destructors release resources;
* move operations preserve ownership;
* copied objects behave correctly;
* worker threads are joined;
* files are closed;
* memory is released;
* exceptions do not leave invalid objects.

## Concurrency Tests

Concurrency tests may include:

* repeated producer-consumer operation;
* queue saturation;
* shutdown during processing;
* repeated worker start and stop cycles;
* long-duration execution;
* queue wraparound;
* race detection.

# Static Analysis

## Cppcheck

```bash
cppcheck \
    --enable=all \
    --std=c++20 \
    --suppress=missingIncludeSystem \
    include src tests
```

## Clang-Tidy

```bash
clang-tidy \
    src/*.cpp \
    -- \
    -std=c++20 \
    -Iinclude
```

Static analysis can identify:

* uninitialized variables;
* unsafe conversions;
* invalid pointer access;
* missing virtual destructors;
* unnecessary copies;
* incorrect move operations;
* suspicious conditions;
* unchecked return values;
* concurrency problems.

# Dynamic Analysis

Valgrind may be used on supported systems.

```bash
valgrind \
    --leak-check=full \
    --show-leak-kinds=all \
    --track-origins=yes \
    ./application
```

Dynamic analysis can detect:

* memory leaks;
* invalid reads;
* invalid writes;
* use of uninitialized memory;
* use-after-free errors;
* incorrect object lifetime;
* invalid resource release.

# Performance Evaluation

Projects involving DSP, queues, concurrency, protocol processing, or real-time operation should include measurable results.

Possible measurements include:

* average execution time;
* maximum execution time;
* processing throughput;
* end-to-end latency;
* queue latency;
* allocation latency;
* memory usage;
* stack usage;
* heap usage;
* dropped-message count;
* dropped-sample count;
* CPU utilization.

### Example Benchmark Output

```text
Frames processed:           1,000,000
Average processing time:    3.1 us/frame
Maximum processing time:    6.4 us/frame
Average queue latency:      1.2 us
Processing throughput:      322,000 frames/s
Memory usage:               24.8 KB
Dropped frames:             0
Processing failures:        0
```

Performance reports should identify:

* processor or test platform;
* operating system;
* compiler;
* compiler version;
* C++ standard;
* optimization level;
* number of iterations;
* input size;
* measurement method.

# Continuous Integration

GitHub Actions may be used to automate:

* GCC builds;
* Clang builds;
* debug builds;
* release builds;
* unit tests;
* sanitizer tests;
* static analysis;
* formatting checks;
* code-coverage generation.

A possible workflow may include:

```text
GCC Debug Build
GCC Release Build
Clang Debug Build
AddressSanitizer Test
UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer Test
ThreadSanitizer Test
Static Analysis
Unit Tests
```

